{"title_page": "Jo\u00ebl Pelier", "text_new": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Jo\u00ebl Pelier\n| image         =\n| fullname      = Jo\u00ebl Pelier\n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1962|3|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Valentigney]], [[France]]\n| height        =\n| weight        =\n| currentteam   = Retired\n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     =\n| amateuryears1 =\n| amateurteam1  =\n| proyears1     =\n| proteam1      =\n| majorwins     = 1 stage 1989 Tour de France\n}}\n'''Jo\u00ebl Pelier''' (born 23 March 1962, in [[Valentigney]]) is a [[France|French]] former professional [[road bicycle racer]].\n\nAfter the final climb of stage 17 in the [[1986 Tour de France]], Pelier collapsed from exhaustion and fell into a 7-hour coma.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n36Q-Fk1Byk&list=PL8601B5412ED5F072 |title=Tour de France 1986 review |publisher=YouTube.com/SBS Television |date= |accessdate=2013-07-28}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1989 Tour de France]], then 27-year-old French [[domestique]] [[Joel Pelier]] had never been watched in his pro career by his parents who were dedicated to caring for Pelier's severely disabled sibling who needed constant attention. Pelier's parents made arrangements to watch stage 6 from near the finish line to which Pelier responded with an attempted lone breakaway. Pelier held out to win the stage by 1 minute and 34 seconds. He rode on his own for 4 and a 1/2 hours through wind and rain for 102 of the stage's 161 miles.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1989-07-08/sports/sp-2524_1_frenchman-wins-stage \"Frenchman Wins Stage; LeMond Leads\" Los Angeles Times, 8 Jul 1989]</ref> It was the then second longest breakaway in Tour de France history after [[Albert Bourlon]] in 1947 and since surpassed by [[Thierry Marie]].<ref name = \"cw\">[http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/archive/382859/1989-tour-de-france-stage-six.html \"1989 Tour de France stage six: Pelier's long break\" Cycling Weekly 13 Jul 2009]</ref> On the podium for the day's presentations a tear drenched Pelier was seen on television saying, \"Mon per, mon per\".<ref name = \"c4\">\"Tour de France\" Channel 4 tv, 7 Jul 1989.</ref> \"This win is so special to me because today is the first time that my mother and father have seen me in the Tour de France,\u2019 said Pelier.<ref name = \"cw\"/>\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;1985\n:Goujounac\n;1987\n:Besan\u00e7on\n;1989\n:Monein\n:Riom-en-Montagne\n:[[1989 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 6\n;1990\n:Vouneuil-sous-Biard\n{{div col end}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{cycling archives|3580}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070808194454/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/riders/us/4740.html Official Tour de France results for Jo\u00ebl Pelier]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pelier, Joel}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Valentigney]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:French Tour de France stage winners]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Doubs]]\n\n\n{{France-cycling-bio-1960s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Jo\u00ebl Pelier\n| image         =\n| fullname      = Jo\u00ebl Pelier\n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1962|3|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Valentigney]], [[France]]\n| height        =\n| weight        =\n| currentteam   = Retired\n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     =\n| amateuryears1 =\n| amateurteam1  =\n| proyears1     =\n| proteam1      =\n| majorwins     = 1 stage 1989 Tour de France\n}}\n'''Jo\u00ebl Pelier''' (born 23 March 1962, in [[Valentigney]]) is a [[France|French]] former professional [[road bicycle racer]].\n\nAfter the final climb of stage 17 in the [[1986 Tour de France]], Pelier collapsed from exhaustion and fell into a 7-hour coma.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n36Q-Fk1Byk&list=PL8601B5412ED5F072 |title=Tour de France 1986 review |publisher=YouTube.com/SBS Television |date= |accessdate=2013-07-28}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1989 Tour de France]], then 27-year-old French [[domestique]] [[Joel Pelier]] had never been watched in his pro career by his parents who were dedicated to caring for Pelier's severely disabled sibling who needed constant attention. Pelier's parents made arrangements to watch stage 6 from near the finish line to which Pelier responded with an attempted lone breakaway. Pelier held out to win the stage by 1 minute and 34 seconds. He rode on his own for 4 and a 1/2 hours through wind and rain for 102 of the stage's 161 miles.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1989-07-08/sports/sp-2524_1_frenchman-wins-stage \"Frenchman Wins Stage; LeMond Leads\" Los Angeles Times, 8 Jul 1989]</ref> It was the then second longest breakaway in Tour de France history after [[Albert Bourlon]] in 1947 and since surpassed by [[Thierry Marie]].<ref name = \"cw\">[http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/archive/382859/1989-tour-de-france-stage-six.html \"1989 Tour de France stage six: Pelier's long break\" Cycling Weekly 13 Jul 2009]</ref> On the podium for the day's presentations a tear drenched Pelier was seen on television saying, \"Mon per, mon per\".<ref name = \"c4\">\"Tour de France\" Channel 4 tv, 7 Jul 1989.</ref> \"This win is so special to me because today is the first time that my mother and father have seen me in the Tour de France,\u2019 said Pelier.<ref name = \"cw\"/>\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;1985\n:Goujounac\n;1987\n:Besan\u00e7on\n;1989\n:Monein\n:Riom-en-Montagne\n:[[1989 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 6\n;1990\n:Vouneuil-sous-Biard\n{{div col end}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{cycling archives|3580}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070808194454/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/riders/us/4740.html Official Tour de France results for Jo\u00ebl Pelier]\n\n=